	"nodes":[
		{"id":"bd2f7f843f1e9f53","type":"text","text":"## <center> sem-4</center>","x":-200,"y":-60,"width":250,"height":60,"color":"6"},
		{"id":"7cfc1afb5762b547","type":"text","text":"***Software Engineering***\n\n**Unit I**\nI**ntroduction to Software Engineering:** Definition, Software Engineering-Layered Technology, Software Characteristics and Components, Software Model: Software Development of Life Cycle Model (SDLC), Waterfall Model, Iterative Waterfall Model, Prototyping Model, Spiral Model, RAD Model\n\n**Unit II**\n**Requirement Engineering:** Definition, Requirement Engineering Activity, Types of Requirements- Functional and Non-Functional Requirements, User and System Requirements, Requirement Documentation (SRS). **Design Concept, Principle and Methods:** Design Fundamentals, Design Principles, Effective Modular Design, Coupling and Cohesion.\n\n**Unit III**\n**Software Metrics, Project Management and Estimation:** Metrics in Process and Project Domains, Software Quality Metrics, Estimation- Software Project Estimation, Decomposition Techniques- Function Point Estimation, Line of Code (LOC) Based Estimation, COCOMO Model\n\n**Unit IV**\n**Software Testing:** Definitions, Software Testing Life Cycle (STLC), Strategic Approach to Software Testing- Verification & Validation, Unit Testing, Integration Testing, Validation Testing, System Testing, Black Box Testing Techniques, White Box Testing Techniques, Acceptance Testing.\n\n**Unit V**\n**AI-Driven Software Engineering:** Al-assisted coding (GitHub Copilot, Code Whisperer, ChatGPT-based coding), AI for requirements analysis, design generation and refactoring, Automated test-case generation using AI, Software engineering with LLMs: opportunities and risks.","x":-413,"y":-640,"width":676,"height":400,"color":"3"},
		{"id":"42bdcf43f35420a9","type":"text","text":"***Web Technologies***\n\n**UNIT I**\n**Fundamentals of Web & HTML:** Internet basics: WWW, HTTP/HTTPS, URL, Domain names, Hosting. Web servers: Apache, Nginx; Web clients; Client-server architecture. **Introduction to HTML:** Structure, tags, attributes, headings, lists, tables, forms. HTML5: semantic tags, audio/video, canvas, media embedding. Web standards (W3C), responsiveness basics, metadata, and favicon.\n\n**UNIT II**\n**CSS & Responsive Web Design:** CSS selectors, properties, colors, borders, margins, padding, box model. CSS3: transitions, animations, transforms, shadows, gradients. Flexbox, Grid Layout. Responsive design: media queries, breakpoints, fluid layouts. Frameworks: Bootstrap / Tailwind basics. UI/UX fundamentals for web pages.\n\n**UNIT III**\n**JavaScript & DOM Programming:** JS basics: variables, data types, operators, loops, functions. Events, event handling, error handling. DOM, BOM, manipulation of HTML elements via JS. ES6+ concepts (let/const, arrow functions, promises, classes, modules). Form validation & input handling. AJAX basics and asynchronous programming (fetch API).\n\n**UNIT IV**\n**Backend Web Development:** HTTP methods: GET, POST, PUT, DELETE; Request/Response cycle. Server-side scripting: Node.js. Routing, templating engines, sessions, cookies, authentication basics. Database connectivity: MySQL / MongoDB. REST API introduction, JSON handling. Web application architecture (2-tier, 3-tier, MVC idea).\n\n**UNIT V**\n**Advanced Web Technologies & Security:** Web frameworks: React, Vue. Web services: REST, SOAP, JSON, XML. Deployment: hosting, DNS, Git/GitHub basics, CI/CD overview. Security: HTTPS, CSRF, XSS, SQL Injection, hashing, authentication vs authorization. Progressive Web\nApps (PWA) basics. Modern tools: npm, Webpack, bundlers, package management.","x":-1200,"y":-470,"width":660,"height":440,"color":"5"},
		{"id":"78038d6707b5c974","type":"text","text":"***Internet of Things***\n\n**Unit I**\n**Introduction to IoT:** Concept and evolution of IoT, comparison of IoT with M2M, CPS and WoT, enabling technologies, IoT architecture and core components. Addressing strategies & Mobility Handling, and overview of predecessors such as WSN, M2M and CPS. Basic IoT networking components and their roles in an IoT ecosystem.\n\n**Unit II**\n**IoT Sensing & Devices:** Sensors - characteristics, types (scalar, multimedia, hybrid, virtual), and sensorial deviations. Actuators - types and characteristics. IoT device design considerations, hardware selection, data formats, and processing topologies including on-site, off-site, and edge/fog/cloud offloading approaches.\n\n**Unit III**\n**Connectivity & Communication:** Connectivity technologies - IEEE 802.15.4, Zigbee, Thread, LoRa, Sigfox, NB-IoT, Wi-Fi, Bluetooth. Communication protocols- IPv6, 6LoWPAN, RPL, QUIC. Data protocols - MQTT, MQTT-SN, CoAP, AMQP, XMPP, SOAP, REST, WebSocket. Discovery protocols -mDNS, UPnP; identification protocols - EPC, uCode, URIs; semantic standards -JSON- LD, Web Thing Model.\n\n**Unit IV**\n**Interoperability & Distributed IoT Computing:** Interoperability concepts and standards including EnOcean, DLNA, Konnex, Lon Works, X-10, AllJoyn, IoTivity and HomeKit. Cloud computing for IoT - virtualization, cloud models, SLA and Sensor-Cloud architecture. Fog computing - fog nodes, architecture, deployment models and IoT applications requiring low latency.\n\n**Unit V**\n**Emerging Technologies, Intelligent Systems & Advanced IoT Applications:** AloT & Edge Intelligence: AI/ML Integration, Real-Time Analytics. Next-Gen Connectivity: 5G/6G IoT, Edge- Fog-Cloud Continuum. Cloud IoT Suites, Applications in Smart Cities, Autonomous Systems.","x":320,"y":-394,"width":760,"height":364,"color":"1"},
		{"id":"62e69c5ece99e1f3","type":"text","text":"***Cloud Computing***\n\n**Unit I**\n**Cloud Computing:** Introduction, Characteristics, Service Models, Deployment Models, Benefits, Challenges, Communications in the Cloud, Distributed and Cloud Computing, NIST Cloud Computing Reference Architecture, Seven Step Model of Migration into a Cloud.\n\n**Unit II**\n**Virtualization:** Basics of Virtualization, Types of Virtualization, Implementation Levels of Virtualization, Virtualization Structures, Tools and Mechanisms, Virtualization of CPU, Memory, I/O Devices, Virtual Clusters and Resource management, Virtualization for Data-center Automation.\n\n**Unit III**\n**Cloud Infrastructure:** Architectural Design of Compute and Storage Clouds, Layered Cloud Architecture Development, Design Challenges, Inter Cloud Resource Management, Resource Provisioning and Platform Deployment, Global Exchange of Cloud Resources.\n\n**Unit IV**\n**Security in the Cloud:** Security Overview, Cloud Security Challenges and Risks, Software-as-a-Service Security, Security Governance, Risk Management, Security Monitoring, Security Architecture Design, Data Security, Application Security, Virtual Machine Security, Identity Management and Access Control.\n\n**Unit V**\n**Programming Model & Industrial Platforms:** Introduction to MapReduce, Hadoop Library from Apache, Google App Engine (GAE), Amazon Web Service (AWS), Microsoft Windows Azure, Market-based management of clouds, MetaCDN, SpotCloud.","x":-870,"y":106,"width":680,"height":360,"color":"4"},
		{"id":"ef0408991286122f","type":"text","text":"***Data Mining & Analysis***\n\n**Unit I**\n**Data Mining:** Fundamentals of data mining, Data Mining Functionalities, Classification of Data Mining systems, Data Mining Task Primitives, Integration of a Data Mining System with a Database or Data Warehouse System, Major issues in Data Mining. **Data Preprocessing:** Need for Preprocessing the Data, Data Cleaning, Data Integration & Transformation, Data Reduction, Discretization and Concept Hierarchy Generation.\n\n**Unit II**\n**Mining Association Rules in Large Databases:** Association Rule Mining: Market Basket Analysis, Basic Concepts, Mining Single Dimensional Boolean Association Rules from Transactional Databases: The Apriori Algorithm, Generating Association Rules from Frequent Items, Improving the Efficiency of Apriori, other Algorithms & their Comparison, Mining Multilevel Association Rules, Multidimensional Association Rules, Constraint Based Association Rule Mining.\n\n**Unit III**\n**Classification:** Problem Definition, General Approaches to solving a classification problem, Evaluation of Classifiers, Classification techniques, Decision Trees-Decision tree Construction, Algorithm for Decision tree Induction, Naive-Bayes Classifier, Bayesian Belief Networks; K- Nearest neighbor classification.\n\n**Unit IV**\n**Clustering:** Clustering Overview, A Categorization of Major Clustering Methods, Partitioning Methods, Hierarchical Methods, Partitioning Clustering-K-Means Algorithm, PAM Algorithm; Hierarchical Clustering- Agglomerative Methods and divisive methods.\n\n**Unit V**\n**Concept of Augmented Analytics:** Automated data preparation, feature engineering, model selection, Introduction to AutoML frameworks, Graph data structures: nodes, edges, temporal graphs, heterogeneous graphs. Graph mining tasks: community detection, link prediction, graph clustering, network anomaly detection, Explainable Data Mining Importance of interpretability in modern ML system","x":49,"y":106,"width":691,"height":494,"color":"2"},
		{"id":"6b6069890bd48853","type":"text","text":"Important topics of IoT:- \n\n* What is IoT?\n* Differences sabke padh lena ( IoT, M2M, CPS, WSN, actuators, sensors, transducers )\n* Features of fault tolerance.\n* Agar question mein architecture likha ho to wahan theory ke saath diagram is compulsory, CPS ka architecture ( 5 c) imp hai padh lena.\n* Mobility, Node Mobility\n* Features of M2M padh lena ( negligible mobility bhi feature hai iska to mention karna in answer)\n* Smart dust, kya hai kaise kaam karta hai and applications sab padhna.\n* Evolution of IoT ( atm, web, smart metre )\n* Ipv4 and ipv6\n* What are the enabling technologies of IoT \n* Components of IoT network ( lan, wan gateway, routers and proxy etc.) \n* Remote anchoring\n* Classification of sensors:- based on power/ input/output \n* Characteristics of sensors\n* Types of actuators \n* Topology offsite and onsite\n* IoT device design consideration for eg size kam, memory jyada etc.\n* Offloading consideration\n* Fog, remote server and cloud","x":1280,"y":-268,"width":467,"height":388},
		{"id":"b0619fc7bcae9129","type":"text","text":"IOT IMP TOPICS\n\n\n* Diffrecnec, Ananlyisis, Based on charcteristics-> IOTvs WOT, vs /mtm\n* Features as per the notes can be asked\n* Architecture \n* Mobility : -\n* What is Node Mobility : Moving from one network to another -> WSN \n* MTM, CPS most important\n* MTM features in boks are given ex: negiligible mobility\nDiffrenec MTM, CPS, IOT, WSN\nActuator, sensor, translutor\nSmart dust working and its applications\nCPS Architecture\n* ATM question of quiz, Evolution Of IT\n* IPv4 and IPv6 (imp)\nWhat are the enabiling technologies of IOT\nEnabiling Technologies of IOT\nIOT newtork compoents : Router, LAN , GATEWAY, WAN, PROXY IOT\nRemote Anchoring  : If your location changes address wouldn't change\nSensor VS Translutor VS Actuator Diffreence\nClassification Of Sensor\nBased on power, output, input\nPower : Active, Passive\nOutput : ANalog , Digital\nScalar, Vector\nSensor Characteristics\nDesign Considerations\n\n\nSimilarily Actuator\nTypes, 7 \nNumetic , Thermal, SMA.....\nTopology : Offsite locations : \nWhat kind of data should be sending in these offsite locations\nToplogoies of offsite , Onsite\niot deesugn principle\nIOT device design consderation\nOff site/Off loading locations and Offloading Consideration\nEdge, Fog, Remote, Server or Cloud\nOffloading Consideration: BAnndwidth, Latency...","x":1280,"y":-780,"width":460,"height":460},
		{"id":"c7ece626aeedfabe","x":-1120,"y":-1000,"width":610,"height":386,"color":"#1eff00","type":"text","text":"I am uploading a PDF containing my subject questions. \n\nInstructions:\n1. Read the PDF carefully.\n2. Solve all questions one by one in the same order.\n3. Give detailed answers suitable for 5-mark college exams.\n4. Use simple language but include proper definitions, explanations, and examples.\n5. If diagrams are required, describe them clearly in text format.\n6. Do not skip any question.\n7. Highlight important keywords for exam preparation.\n\nSubject: [ Name]\nUnit: [ Name  ]"},
